      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i need help writing a rejection email for a candidate. they made it to the final round for a senior dev role here in austin but we decided to go with someone else. they were actually really strong in system design and had great culture fit, so it was a tough call. i want to be professional and empathetic so we don't burn the bridge, but i need to be firm that it's a no. can you help me draft something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here are a few options for your rejection email, but I've kept the tone professional, empathetic, and firm, which is important when dealing with strong candidates. You can tailor this to your company's voice, but remember to keep the *real* reason for the decision vague, even if it was a near-tie, to avoid arguments.\n\n**Option 1: Warm and Appreciative (Good for keeping the bridge very open)**\n\nSubject: Update on the Senior Developer Role at [Company Name]\n\nDear [Candidate Name],\n\nThank you so much for investing your time and energy into the final rounds for the Senior Developer position. We were genuinely impressed with your technical depth, particularly your insights into system design, and your alignment with our team culture. The decision was incredibly difficult; we had several exceptionally strong candidates, and this was a tough call, as one of the final choices.\n\nUltimately, we have decided to move forward with another candidate whose specific experience was a slightly closer match to the immediate needs of this particular role at this moment. Please know this decision was not a reflection of your talent, which is clearly top-tier.\n\nWe truly value the time you spent with us, and we hope you'",
